**W2-D7-Virtual_Environment_Setup**
Goal: Every Django project needs its own isolated set of packages — venv prevents different projects' dependencies from conflicting with each other. This is non-negotiable before starting Django next week.

No new Python code today — this is a terminal/setup task.

Run these commands in your room laptop terminal, inside a project folder:

```bash
# Create virtual environment
python -m venv venv

# Activate it (Windows)
venv\Scripts\activate

# Activate it (Mac/Linux)
source venv/bin/activate
```

Once activated, you'll see `(venv)` appear at the start of your terminal line — that's confirmation it's active.

```bash
# Install Django inside the venv
pip install django

# Confirm it installed
django-admin --version
```

Task: Deactivate the venv using `deactivate`, then run `django-admin --version` again — notice it fails or shows a different/no version, proving Django was installed only inside that venv, not globally on your system.

Task: Reactivate the venv, run `pip freeze` — see a list of installed packages with exact versions. This is what goes into a `requirements.txt` file later (used in every real project so others can recreate your exact environment).

Task: Run `pip freeze > requirements.txt` — open the file, see Django listed with its version number.

Break it: Try installing a package (e.g. `pip install requests`) while the venv is NOT activated. Then activate the venv and run `pip freeze` — notice `requests` is missing from this venv's list, since it got installed globally/elsewhere instead. This shows exactly why forgetting to activate venv causes confusing "why isn't this package found" bugs later.

Real Coder Note: Always activate your venv before installing anything or running your project — forgetting this is one of the most common beginner mistakes, and it causes confusing errors that look unrelated to the actual cause.

